In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims September 23-29, 2012, as National Historically Black Colleges and Universities Week. He acknowledges the founders of the first colleges and universities for African Americans, who believed that education is a path to freedom and success. Obama highlights the important role that Historically Black Colleges and Universities (HBCUs) have played in providing access to higher education and instilling pride and history in students. He emphasizes the contributions of HBCU graduates in shaping the progress of the United States through championing equality, arts, economy, education, healthcare, and defense. The President also emphasizes the importance of HBCUs in moving the country forward by cultivating leaders in all areas of society and working towards the goal of having the highest proportion of college graduates in the world by 2020. Obama calls upon educators, public officials, professional organizations, corporations, and all Americans to observe the week with appropriate programs and activities that recognize the contributions of HBCUs and their alumni to the country.